  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraping pipeline (114 ATS sources → SQLite dedup → notifiers), not a web app. There's no React/frontend code anywhere in the repo, so I've mapped the requested categories onto what actually exists: SQLite N+1s, redundant per-item computation, and retained-memory patterns in a fetch→filter→dedup pipeline.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nWith 114 sources × up to hundreds of jobs each, a single run can process thousands of `Job`s. Today each one does its own round trip:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)          # individual INSERT\n    else:\n        ...\n        self._update(cur, job, now)          # or individual UPDATE\n```\nThat's 1 SELECT + 1 INSERT/UPDATE *per job* — classic N+1, just against SQLite instead of a network DB. Fix: bulk-load existing hashes once, then batch the writes.\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))  # 1 query\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    if new:\n        cur.executemany(INSERT_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    if changed:\n        cur.executemany(UPDATE_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nTurns O(n) round trips into O(1) + 3 batched statements.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`match()` is called once per fetched job, and it calls `_compile()` on every call:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiles every call\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiles every call\n```\nFor N jobs and K keywords, that's O(N×K) `re.compile()` calls when it should be O(K). Fix — compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include_p = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_p = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_p, exclude=exclude_p, locations=..., cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `fetchers.py:543` (Meta fetcher runs each regex twice)\n\n```python\ntok = lambda p: (re.search(p, page) or [None, \"\"])[1] if re.search(p, page) else \"\"\n```\n`re.search(p, page)` executes twice per call — once for the ternary condition, once in the body — against the full careers-page HTML, for every token (`lsd`, `__spin_r`, `__spin_b`, `__spin_t`). Fix:\n\n```python\ndef tok(p: str) -> str:\n    m = re.search(p, page)\n    return m.group(1) if m else \"\"\n```\nHalves the regex work for this fetcher with no behavior change.\n\n### 4. Retained memory — `Job.raw` payload kept for the whole pipeline\n\nMost parsers (`parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, `parse_workday`, etc.) store the *entire* source JSON record in `Job.raw`. Those `Job` objects stay alive through fetch → filter → `store.diff()` for the whole run — across 114 sources with potentially thousands of jobs, that's thousands of full raw payloads resident in memory simultaneously even though only `to_row()` (which drops `raw`) and a few named fields ever get read after parsing. Not a \"leak\" in the classic sense (it's freed at process exit, and this is a short-lived CLI run), but it's unnecessary peak-memory pressure. If board sizes grow, consider dropping unused keys from `raw` at parse time (as `parse_google`/`parse_meta`/`parse_deshaw` already do) instead of storing full source dicts.\n\n### 5. Minor leak-on-error path — `store.py:36-41` (`Store.__init__`)\n\n```python\ndef __init__(self, path):\n    self.conn = sqlite3.connect(str(path))\n    self.conn.executescript(_SCHEMA)\n    self._migrate()\n    self.conn.commit()\n```\nIf `executescript`/`_migrate` raises (e.g. a corrupt/locked DB file), `__init__` never returns, so `with Store(...)` never binds and `__exit__`/`close()` never runs — the raw `sqlite3.Connection` (and its file descriptor) leaks until GC finalizes it. Wrap the body in `try/except` that closes `self.conn` before re-raising, or open the connection as the very last step after schema/migration succeed on a temp connection.\n\n### 6. Caching/concurrency opportunity — Workday pagination is unnecessarily sequential\n\n`fetch_workday` (fetchers.py:422-470) is the one fetcher whose first response includes `total`, so unlike Google/Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix (which must page one-at-a-time to detect the end), Workday could fetch page 1, learn `total`, then fetch the remaining `ceil(total/page_size) - 1` pages concurrently via `asyncio.gather` instead of awaiting them one by one. For large Workday boards this cuts wall-clock roughly proportional to page count.\n\n### Not applicable\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend exists in this repo (pure Python backend), so there's nothing to check here.\n- **HTTP-level caching (ETags/If-None-Match)**: none of the ATS APIs are queried conditionally today; low priority since job boards change frequently enough that conditional GETs would rarely save a fetch, but worth a look if bandwidth/rate-limit issues emerge with 114 sources.\n\n**Priority**: fix #1 (N+1 SQL) and #2 (regex recompilation) first — both scale with total job count across all 114 sources and are the actual bottlenecks as the source list grows; #3 and #6 are small, isolated wins; #4/#5 are low-severity but easy to harden.\n",
